ocs-operator.v4.20.10-rhodf  Succeeded

So OLM is tracking the 4.20 channel and has installed 4.20.10.

The only reason you still see:

ocs-operator-stable-4.19-redhat-operator-index-openshift-marketplace

is that this is the Subscription's metadata.name. Kubernetes object names are immutable; OLM does not rename them when you switch channels or upgrade versions.

You can verify:

oc get sub ocs-operator-stable-4.19-redhat-operator-index-openshift-marketplace \
-n openshift-storage -o yaml | grep "^  name:"

You'll see that's simply the object's name.

A common analogy:

You create a VM called test-server.

Later it runs RHEL 8, then RHEL 9.

The VM name remains test-server.


Similarly:

Subscription created when ODF 4.19 was installed.

Channel changed to stable-4.20.

Operator upgraded to 4.20.10.

Subscription name remains unchanged.


The authoritative version indicators are:

oc get storagecluster -n openshift-storage

→ 4.20.10

oc get csv -n openshift-storage

→ 4.20.10-rhodf

oc get sub -n openshift-storage -o jsonpath='{.items[*].spec.channel}'

→ stable-4.20

All three confirm you're on ODF 4.20.10.

There is nothing left to fix regarding the Subscription name. It is expected behavior.
